2. TreeMap<String,Integer> (ordered by string length)
The comparator treats strings of the same length as equal, so later puts with the same length replace the existing value.

Bash

Copy
merge("dd",4,sum)      → {"dd":4}
merge("fff",6,sum)     → {"dd":4, "fff":6}
put("c",3)             → {"c":3, "dd":4, "fff":6}
put("aa",1)            → length 2 replaces "dd": {"c":3, "dd":1, "fff":6}
put("bb",2)            → length 2 replaces "dd": {"c":3, "dd":2, "fff":6}
merge("e",5,sum)       → length 1 ("c") present → 3+5=8
                         → {"c":8, "dd":2, "fff":6}
Iteration follows the natural order (shortest length first):

Bash

Copy
c:8 dd:2 fff:6 
3. LinkedHashMap<Integer,String> (access‑order, removes eldest when size > 3)
Access‑order moves an accessed entry to the most‑recently‑used end; insertion also places the new entry at that end.
removeEldestEntry removes the least‑recently‑used entry when the size exceeds 3.

Bash

Copy
put(4,"D")   → [4]
put(3,"C")   → [4,3]
get(2)       → absent → no change
get(1)       → absent → no change
put(1,"A")   → [4,3,1]
put(2,"B")   → [4,3,1,2] → size>3 → remove eldest 4 → [3,1,2]
put(5,"E")   → [3,1,2,5] → size>3 → remove eldest 3 → [1,2,5]
Final LRU‑to‑MRU order: 1 → "A", 2 → "B", 5 → "E".

