4. IdentityHashMap<Integer,String> (uses == for keys, System.identityHashCode for buckets)
a and b are the same cached Integer(127).
c and d are the same cached Integer(128).

Bash

Copy
put(b,"Y")      → {127:"Y"}
put(a,"X")      → same object as b → value replaced → {127:"X"}
put(c,"Z")      → {127:"X",128:"Z"}
put(d,"W")      → same object as c → value replaced → {127:"X",128:"W"}
The map therefore contains two entries: 127 → "X" and 128 → "W".
Iteration order follows the internal hash table; with the default capacity it ends up as the insertion order of the distinct keys, giving:

